			<ns0:name>cbif...@google.com</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/106111281808211158579/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">Since we use a stock llvm-gcc, the default libgcc that we link into 
untrusted programs doesn't validate.  We need a sandboxed libgcc.

This may include:
- Replacing inline assembly fragments or .S files with either C or 
carefully-written sandboxed assembly.
- Some hacking of GCC build environments (since libgcc isn't really set up 
to build apart from GCC).
- Etc.

Note that since we control the hardware requirements, we may be able to chop 
out parts of libgcc (like floating point emulation).</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2009-12-17T22:52:34.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2009-11-23T21:27:42.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:status>Fixed</ns2:status><ns2:owner>
